SIMPLE: pythagorean
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pythagorean
<hw>Pyth`a*go"re*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Pythagoreus</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining to
Pythagoras (a Greek philosopher, born about 582 <sc>b. c.</sc>), or his
philosophy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The central thought of the <qex>Pythagorean</qex> philosophy is
the idea of number, the recognition of the numerical and mathematical
relations of things.</q> <rj><qau>Encyc. Brit.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pythagorean proposition</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>,
<cd>the theorem that the square described upon the hypothenuse of a
plane right-angled triangle is equal to the sum of the squares described
upon the other two sides.</cd><-- = Pythagorean theorem. --> --
<col><b>Pythagorean system</b></col> <fld>(Astron.)</fld>, <cd>the
commonly received system of astronomy, first taught by Pythagoras, and
afterward revived by Copernicus, whence it is also called the
<altname>Copernican system</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Pythagorean
letter</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Y.</er></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pythagorean</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pythagorean
<hw>Pyth`a*go"re*an</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A follower of
Pythagoras; one of the school of philosophers founded by
Pythagoras.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pythagoreanism</ent>⟦br⟧
